This leads to two cases: 1. \( n = a^2 \) and \( n + 1 = 2b^2 \) 2. \( n = 2a^2 \) and \( n + 1 = b^2 \) **Case 1: \( n = a^2 \) and \( n + 1 = 2b^2 \)** This gives the Pell equation \( a^2 - 2b^2 = -1 \). The solutions to this Pell equation generate triangular numbers that are perfect squares. The solutions are \( (a, b) = (1, 1), (7, 5), (41, 29), (239, 169), \ldots \). The corresponding triangular numbers are \( 1, 36, 1225, 1631432881, \ldots \). **Case 2: \( n = 2a^2 \) and \( n + 1 = b^2 \)** This gives the Pell equation \( b^2 - 2a^2 = 1 \). The solutions to this Pell equation generate triangular numbers that are perfect squares. The solutions are \( (b, a) = (3, 2), (7, 5), (17, 12), (41, 29), (99, 70), \ldots \). The corresponding triangular numbers are \( 36, 1225, 48024900, \ldots \).
